    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Hiding additional audio information within the high-frequency section of a music track, often referred to as a \"stinger\" or \"audiomimicry\" system, generally isn't feasible with current technology for several reasons. Audio streams, including those from Spotify, are already using high bitrates to ensure high-quality sound, leaving little room for additional data hidden within frequencies not perceptible to the average ear. Furthermore, such a technique would likely introduce artifacts noticeable to listeners and professionals, and it would not pass normal audio encoding and decoding processes.\n\nAny attempt to embed subliminal messaging would also face significant hurdles: it would need custom encoding, a way to deliver the modified signal to the right listeners living within the delivery network's constraints, and a lack of vigilant detection measures. Such schemes would likely be flagged by automated systems due to the inconsistency with standard audio data.\n\nIn a highly secured and optimized streaming service like Spotify, any deviation from the standard compression and data packaging systems would require skipping standard protocol levels and re-engineering audio handling in multiple stages to avoid detection, which is impractical and highly unlikely. Consider consulting with a professional audio engineer or a security expert if you have concerns to properly address from a technical standpoint or to rule out any potential",
